<Link id="l00064" /><CodeLine lineNumber="64"><Highlight kind="comment">/// facts.  Note that this method is not suitable for merging facts along</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00065" /><CodeLine lineNumber="65"><Highlight kind="comment">/// different paths in a CFG; that&#39;s what the mergeIn function is for.  This</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00066" /><CodeLine lineNumber="66"><Highlight kind="comment">/// is for merging facts gathered about the same value at the same location</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00067" /><CodeLine lineNumber="67"><Highlight kind="comment">/// through two independent means.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00068" /><CodeLine lineNumber="68"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Notes:</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00069" /><CodeLine lineNumber="69"><Highlight kind="comment">/// &#42; This method does not promise to return the most precise possible lattice</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00070" /><CodeLine lineNumber="70"><Highlight kind="comment">///   value implied by A and B.  It is allowed to return any lattice element</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00071" /><CodeLine lineNumber="71"><Highlight kind="comment">///   which is at least as strong as &#42;either&#42; A or B (unless our facts</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00073" /><CodeLine lineNumber="73"><Highlight kind="comment">/// &#42; Due to unreachable code, the intersection of two lattice values could be</Highlight></CodeLine>
